ourney for Marshall. Even as his belief in the equalizing power of law was challenged during his career as a Supreme Court justice, and in Kenya the new government sacrificed the rights he cherished, Kenya's founding moment remained for him a time and place when all things had seemed possible.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aCivil rightsxSourcesxHistoryxKenya. 0aCivil rightszKenyaxHistoryvSources. 0aConstitutional historyxSourcesxKenya. 0aConstitutional historyzKenyavSources. 0aJudgesxBiographyxUnited States. 0aJudgeszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aAfrica.  aAfrican American activist.  aAfrican Americans.  aAmerica.  aBlack Power.  aBritain.  aBritish.  aJim Crow.  aKenya.  aKenyan leaders.  aLyndon Johnson.  aSupreme Court justice.  aThurgood Marshall.  aU.S. Supreme Court.  aactivists.  abill of rights.  acivil rights lawyers.  acivil rights reform.  acivil rights.  acolonial rule.  acolonialism.  ademocratic rights.  aequality.  aindependence.  alegal reform.  alegal system.  arace.  aracial riots.  aracism.  arule of law.  asocial change.  aurban violence.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400839896zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400839896423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400839896.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5